===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} [[#French|combustion]], from {{etyl|la|fr}} {{m|la|combustio}}, from {{m|la|comburere||to burn}}, itself from the intensifying prefix [[com-]] + the root [[burere]] (a faulty sep. of [[amburere]] "to burn around", itself from [[ambi-]] + [[urere]] "to burn, singe"); equivalent to {{suffix|en|combust|ion}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/kəmˈbʌs.tʃən/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-combustion.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|chemistry}} The act or process of [[burn]]ing.
# A process where two [[chemical]]s are combined to produce [[heat]].
# A process wherein a [[fuel]] is combined with [[oxygen]], usually at high temperature, releasing [[heat]].
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} Violent [[agitation]], [[tumult]].
#* '''c. 1665''', John Worthington, "The Author's Life", in ''The Works of the Pious and Profoundly-learned Joseph Mede''
#*: There [were] great '''combustions''' and divisions among the heads of the university.
#* {{RQ:Dryden Aureng-zebe|passage=But say from whence this new '''combustion''' springs.}}

